issue.title: Next.js App Router, createServerComponentClient fails when using 'next dev --turbo'
issue.body:
# Bug report

<!-- 

⚠️ We receive a lot of bug reports which have already been solved or discussed. If you are looking for help, please try these first:

- Docs: https://docs.supabase.com
- Discussions: https://github.com/supabase/supabase/discussions
- Discord: https://discord.supabase.com

Before opening a bug report, please verify the following: 

-->

- [X ] I confirm this is a bug with Supabase, not with my own application. 
- [ X ] I confirm I have searched the [Docs](https://docs.supabase.com), GitHub [Discussions](https://github.com/supabase/supabase/discussions), and [Discord](https://discord.supabase.com). 

## Describe the bug

Occurs when using pnpm.
Occurs when using the Next.js App Router.
Occurs in Server Components that use `createServerComponentClient`.
Runs fine when using `npm run dev` as usual, without Turbo.
Repro URL below.

The following gets console logged in the VSCode terminal:

```
ModuleBuildError: error - node_modules/.pnpm/node-gyp-build@4.6.1/node_modules/node-gyp-build/node-gyp-build.js:22:10  Error resolving commonjs request

  20 | 
  21 | function load (dir) {
> 22 |   return runtimeRequire(load.resolve(dir))
     |           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
> 23 | }
     | ^
  24 | 
  25 | load.resolve = load.path = function (dir) {
  26 |   dir = path.resolve(dir || '.')
unable to resolve dynamic
It was not possible to find the requested file.
    Parsed request as written in source code: dynamic
    Path where resolving has started: [project]/node_modules/.pnpm/node-gyp-build@4.6.1/node_modules/node-gyp-build/node-gyp-build.js
    Type of request: commonjs request
    Import map: No import map entry
```

## To Reproduce

- [Clone this repo](https://github.com/baufometic/supabase-turbo-issue)
- Visit `/user/dashboard`

## System information

- Ubuntu 22.04
- VSCode 1.82.2
- PNPM 8.7.6
- Chrome / Chromium / Firefox
- @supabase/auth-helpers-nextjs: 0.8.1,
- @supabase/supabase-js 2.34.0

- Version of Node.js: 18.18.0

## Additional context
Doesn't occur when running regular `npm run dev`

comment.body: I don't believe this is a supabase issue, I'm going through the new https://nextjs.org/learn tutorial which doesn't include supabase at all, and I get this error on an async server component when anywhere in the import chain includes importing from '@vercel/postgres'

issue.title: Fields in primary table returned as null in deeply nested query when using .single() and wildcard * in .select()
issue.body:
# Bug report

- [x] I confirm this is a bug with Supabase, not with my own application. 
- [x] I confirm I have searched the [Docs](https://docs.supabase.com), GitHub [Discussions](https://github.com/supabase/supabase/discussions), and [Discord](https://discord.supabase.com). 

## Describe the bug

When performing a deeply nested query using supabase-js to select data from a table (company_profiles) and its related tables, some fields in the primary table are returned as null even though they have values in the database. This issue specifically occurs when using a wildcard * in the .select() method to fetch all columns from the products related table and when the .single() method is used.
## To Reproduce

Here's the problematic query and the corresponding Prisma schema to reproduce the issue:
```sql
model company_profiles {
    company_id  String  @id @db.Uuid
    quote       String? @db.VarChar(230)
    quote_fullname String?
    // ... other fields
    products    products[]
}
model products {
    product_id  String  @id @db.Uuid
    // ... other fields
    company_id  String  @db.Uuid
    company_profile company_profiles @relation(fields: [company_id], references: [company_id])
}
```
```js
  const { data } = await supabase
      .from('company_profiles')
      .select('*, products(*)')
      .eq('url', slug);
```


Steps to reproduce the behavior, please provide code snippets or a repository:

- Define a table company_profiles with fields including quote and quote_fullname.
- Define a related table products that has a relation back to company_profiles.
- Execute the above query with the .single() method.
- Observe that the quote and quote_fullname fields are returned as null even though they have values in the database.

it could be that you need to add more fields to the company_profiles table to it to happen but it seems that random fields that actually have data are set to null. The issue seems to stem from the usage of products(*) in the .select() query. When I specify the fields explicitly like products(name), the problem does not occur. Interestingly, the issue also goes away when the .single() method is not used.

## Expected behavior

All the fields from the company_profiles table should be returned with their actual values, not as null, when performing the nested query, even when using .single()

## Screenshots

If applicable, add screenshots to help explain your problem.

## System information

- OS: [e.g. macOS, Windows]
- Browser (if applies) Chrome
- Version of supabase-js: ~2.38.4
- Version of Node.js: [e.g. 18.17.0

comment.diff_hunk:
@@ -0,0 +1,103 @@
+import Layout from '~/layouts/DefaultGuideLayout'
+
+export const meta = {
+  id: 'sessions',
+  title: 'User Sessions',
+  description: 'Control and manage user sessions.',
+}
+
+Supabase Auth provides fine-grained control over your user's sessions.
+
+A session is created when a user signs in. It is represented by the Supabase Auth access token in the form of a JWT, and a refresh token which is a unique string.
+
+Access tokens are designed to be short lived, usually between 5 minutes and 1 hour. You can exchange a refresh token only once to get a new access and refresh token pair.
+
+This process is called **refreshing the session.** 
+
+By default, there's no limit to the number of sessions a user can have on Supabase Auth. This behavior can be controlled in the following ways.
+
+- By restricting the number of sessions a user can have.
+- By controlling the lifetime of a session.
+
+A session can terminate, depending on configuration, when:
+
+- The user clicks sign out.
+- The user changes their password or performs a security sensitive action.
+- It times out due to inactivity.
+- It reaches its maximum lifetime.
+- A new session for the same user was started.
+
+## Controlling the lifetime of a session
+
+<Admonition type="note">
+
+This feature is only available on Pro plans and up.
+
+</Admonition>
+
+Supabase Auth can be configured to limit the lifetime of a user's session. By default, all sessions are active until the user clicks log out or performs some other action that terminates a session.
+
+In some applications, it's useful or required from a security point of view to ensure that users authenticate often, or that sessions are not left active on devices for too long.
+
+There are two ways in which you can limit the lifetime of a session:
+
+- By enabling timeboxed sessions which terminate after a fixed amount of time.
+- By enabling inactivity timeout, such that if a session remains unrefreshed for too long it will be terminated.
+
+To make sure that users are required to re-authenticate periodically, you can select the _Enforce timeboxed sessions_ option in the Auth configuration screen for your project.
+
+To make sure that sessions expire after a period of inactivity, you can select and configure the _Terminate inactive sessions_ option.
+
+Sessions are not proactively terminated when you change these settings, but rather the check is enforced whenever a session is refreshed next.
+
+## Restricting the number of sessions per user
+
+<Admonition type="note">
+
+This feature is only available on Pro plans and up.
+
+</Admonition>
comment.body: Yeah. When we roll out with the session management APIs we can think about it differently I guess.
